nslookup static-server2.service.consul     (Not Working)
nslookup static-server2.virtual.consul     (Not Working)


Q. This is working:
~ # curl static-server2
"hello world from exported service"

but below does not:
dig @127.0.0.1 static-server2  

WHY?

Answer:

This is the final piece of the DNS puzzle. You are seeing curl succeed because it is "lazy" (it uses the OS search path), while dig fails because it is "strict" (it only looks for the exact name you typed).
1. The "Short Name" Secret
When you run curl static-server2, the OS resolver looks at /etc/resolv.conf. It sees a list of search domains like:
default.svc.cluster.local
svc.cluster.local
cluster.local
The OS (curl) does this:
"Hey 127.0.0.1, do you have static-server2.default.svc.cluster.local?"
Consul says: "I don't know that name, let me ask CoreDNS (10.11.0.10)."
CoreDNS says: "Yes, here is the IP."
curl gets the IP and connects. Success.
2. Why dig @127.0.0.1 static-server2 fails
dig is a technical tool designed to query exactly what you tell it to query. It does not automatically use the search path.
dig does this:
"Hey 127.0.0.1, do you have a record for the literal name static-server2?"
Consul looks in its .consul registry. It doesn't see a service just named static-server2 (it expects something like static-server2.service.consul).
Consul returns NXDOMAIN (No such domain).
dig shows you the failure.
3. How to make dig work
If you want dig to behave like curl and follow the Kubernetes search paths, you have to add the +search flag:
dig @127.0.0.1 static-server2 +search
Alternatively, you can provide the Fully Qualified Domain Name (FQDN), which is what the OS is actually sending behind the scenes:
dig @127.0.0.1 static-server2.default.svc.cluster.local






